-- Merchants Bank, Sun Hung Kai, Taiping Insurance: Hong Kong Equity Preview
-- Hanny Wan
-- 2010-09-21T01:21:45Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-21/merchants-bank-sun-hung-kai-taiping-insurance-hong-kong-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The  following  companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  
 The  Hang Seng Index  was little changed at 21,977.34. The
 Hang Seng China Enterprises Index , which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, declined 0.1 percent to 12,164.65.  
 Chinese developers: China may announce property tax
measures before or after the National Day holidays in October
which takes place from Oct. 1 to Oct. 7, China Business News
reported, citing an unidentified person.  
 China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd.  (688 HK), controlled
by the nation’s construction ministry, advanced 1 percent to
HK$17.58.  China Resources Land Ltd.  (1109 HK), a state-
controlled developer, gained 1.3 percent to HK$17.24.  
 China Merchants Bank Co.  (3968 HK): The bank said it will
appoint  Fu Yuning  as chairman, replacing the retiring Qin Xiao,
pending approval from the China Banking Regulatory Commission.  
 Separately, the lender’s proposal to set up a Taiwan office
was rejected by the island’s Financial Supervisory Commission,
the Economic Daily News reported. The stock dropped 0.1 percent
to HK$19.94.  
 China Taiping Insurance Holdings Co.  (966 HK): The insurer
will dispose of its 100% stake in Ming An China, which is
principally engaged in the property and casualty insurance
business, through a public auction in the Tianjin Property
Rights Exchange in China, according to a statement. Taiping slid
0.9 percent to HK$26.55.  
 Far East Consortium International Ltd.  (35 HK): The company
seeks between $142 million and $192 million in a share sale of
its Kosmopolito Hotels International Ltd. unit, according to
terms of the offer obtained by Bloomberg News. Far East, a real
estate developer and hotel operator, climbed 1.8 percent to
HK$2.31.  
 Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd.  (16 HK): The world’s biggest
developer by market value said full-year underlying profit rose
12 percent to HK$13.9 billion ($1.8 billion) after rental income
from its offices and shopping malls increased. That’s below the
HK$14.1 billion average estimate of 17 analysts surveyed by
Bloomberg. The stock advanced 1.4 percent to HK$122.10.  
